# LIGMA — Functional Requirements Specification

**Project:** Let’s Integrate Groups, Manage Anything (LIGMA)
**Type:** Real-Time Collaborative Workspace

---

# 1. Introduction

## 1.1 Purpose

This document defines the functional requirements for LIGMA, a real-time collaborative workspace that bridges ideation (canvas) and execution (task board) by automatically extracting actionable insights from user input.

---

## 1.2 Scope

The system enables multiple users to collaborate on an infinite canvas, create and manipulate nodes, and automatically convert ideas into structured tasks using an intent-aware processing layer.

---

# 2. User Management

## 2.1 Authentication

* The system shall allow users to register with:

  * Name
  * Email
  * Password
* The system shall allow secure login and logout.
* The system shall maintain authenticated sessions using tokens (JWT or equivalent).

---

## 2.2 Roles

The system shall support the following roles:

* Lead
* Contributor
* Viewer

---

## 2.3 Role Assignment

* The system shall assign roles per workspace/session.
* The system shall allow dynamic role updates without requiring a page reload.

---

## 2.4 Session Access

* Users shall be able to:

  * Create a new session
  * Join an existing session via link or session ID

---

# 3. Canvas Functionality

## 3.1 Infinite Canvas

* The system shall provide:

  * Infinite scrolling canvas
  * Zoom in/out functionality
  * Smooth panning

---

## 3.2 Node Creation

Users shall be able to create:

* Sticky notes
* Text blocks
* Shapes (rectangle, circle, etc.)
* Freehand drawings

---

## 3.3 Node Properties

Each node shall contain:

* Unique identifier (node_id)
* Type (text, shape, sticky, drawing)
* Content (text or drawing data)
* Position (x, y coordinates)
* Size (width, height)
* Author (user_id)
* Timestamp

---

## 3.4 Node Operations

Users shall be able to:

* Create nodes
* Move nodes
* Resize nodes
* Edit content
* Delete nodes

---

## 3.5 Node Addressability

* Each node shall be independently addressable.
* Each node shall be retrievable using its unique ID.

---

# 4. Real-Time Collaboration

## 4.1 Multi-User Editing

* The system shall allow multiple users to edit the canvas simultaneously.
* Changes shall propagate to all users in real time (≤ 2 seconds).

---

## 4.2 Delta Updates

* The system shall transmit only incremental changes (deltas), not full canvas state.

---

## 4.3 Cursor Presence

* The system shall display:

  * Each user’s cursor
  * User label (name or ID)
* Cursor positions shall update in real time.

---

# 5. Conflict Resolution

## 5.1 Concurrent Editing

* The system shall handle simultaneous edits on the same node.

---

## 5.2 Merge Strategy

* The system shall implement a conflict resolution mechanism (e.g., CRDT or OT).
* The system shall ensure consistent merged output across all clients.

---

## 5.3 State Consistency

* All clients shall eventually converge to the same state.
* No updates shall be lost during concurrent edits.

---

# 6. Intent-Aware Task Extraction

## 6.1 Intent Classification

The system shall classify node content into:

* Action Item
* Decision
* Open Question
* Reference

---

## 6.2 Processing Time

* Intent classification shall occur within 3 seconds of content update.

---

## 6.3 Automatic Task Creation

* Nodes classified as "Action Item" shall automatically generate tasks.

---

## 6.4 Task Metadata

Each task shall include:

* task_id
* node_id (reference)
* author
* timestamp

---

## 6.5 Data Integrity

* Tasks shall not duplicate node content.
* Tasks shall maintain references to original nodes.

---

# 7. Task Board

## 7.1 Task Display

* The system shall display a live-updating list of tasks.

---

## 7.2 Navigation

* Clicking a task shall:

  * Navigate to the associated canvas node
  * Highlight or focus the node

---

## 7.3 Real-Time Updates

* Task board shall update across all users without reload.

---

# 8. Node-Level Access Control (RBAC)

## 8.1 Node Permissions

* Each node shall maintain its own access control list (ACL).

---

## 8.2 Permission Types

Permissions shall include:

* View
* Edit
* Comment
* Lock

---

## 8.3 Enforcement

* Permissions shall be enforced:

  * On the frontend (UI restrictions)
  * On the backend (server-side validation)

---

## 8.4 Dynamic Updates

* Permission changes shall take effect immediately without reload.

---

# 9. Append-Only Event Log

## 9.1 Event Storage

* Every mutation shall be stored as an immutable event.

---

## 9.2 Event Types

Events shall include:

* NodeCreated
* NodeUpdated
* NodeDeleted
* PermissionChanged

---

## 9.3 Immutability

* Events shall never be modified or deleted.

---

## 9.4 Event Viewer

* The system shall display:

  * Event type
  * Timestamp
  * User ID

---

# 10. WebSocket Management

## 10.1 Connection Handling

* The system shall maintain persistent WebSocket connections.

---

## 10.2 Broadcast System

* Updates shall be broadcast to all connected clients efficiently.

---

## 10.3 Reconnection Handling

* The system shall detect disconnections and allow reconnection.

---

## 10.4 Event Replay

* On reconnection:

  * The system shall send only missed events.
  * Clients shall provide last received event ID.

---

# 11. Deployment Requirements

## 11.1 Hosting

* Backend shall be deployed on Render.

---

## 11.2 Accessibility

* The system shall be publicly accessible via URL.

---

## 11.3 Demo Readiness

* The deployed system shall support live demonstration.

---

# 12. Optional Features (Bonus)

## 12.1 Time-Travel Replay

* The system shall allow replay of session history using stored events.

---

## 12.2 Presence Heatmap

* The system shall visualize areas with high user activity.

---

## 12.3 AI Summary Export

* The system shall generate structured summaries of sessions.

